👉 Problem 2: Shortest Subarray With Sum ≥ Target

Find the smallest subarray length whose sum is at least target.

You are given:

nums → positive integers

target → required minimum sum

Return:

Length of the shortest subarray with sum ≥ target

If none exists → return 0

✨ Key Idea

This is a classic expanding + shrinking sliding window.

Because all numbers are positive, the window sum only increases when R moves right — so shrinking works correctly.

✨ Flashcard

“Expand R to grow sum.
When total ≥ target → shrink from L to find smaller valid window.
Track minimum window length.”

⚡ Full Approach (Step-by-Step, No Code)
Step 1 — Use two pointers

L = start of window

R = end of window

total = sum of current window

Step 2 — Expand the window by moving R

For each R:

total += nums[R]


This makes the window sum bigger.

Step 3 — When total ≥ target → shrink

While the window is “heavy enough”:

Update the minimum length:

length = min(length, R - L + 1)


Remove the leftmost element:

total -= nums[L]
L += 1


This tries to make the window smaller while still meeting the sum requirement.

Step 4 — Continue until R reaches end
Step 5 — If no window ever met the target

Return 0.

🧠 Mental Picture

Imagine dragging a window that grows until it hits the target sum.

Then you tighten the window from the left to see if a smaller valid window exists.

Repeat until the end.

⏱️ Complexity
Operation	Cost
Time	O(n)
Space	O(1)

Only linear time because each pointer (L and R) moves at most n steps.

👉 Problem: Two Pointers (two_pointers.py)
👉 Problem 1: Check if a String is a Palindrome

Determine whether a given string reads the same forwards and backwards.

You are given:

word → a string of characters

You must return:

true if the string is a palindrome

false otherwise

✨ Key Idea

Use the two-pointer pattern:

One pointer starts at the left

One pointer starts at the right

Compare characters while moving inward.

The moment characters don’t match → it’s not a palindrome.

If we reach the center without mismatches → it is a palindrome.

✨ Flashcard

“Use two pointers from both ends.
If characters ever differ → not a palindrome.
If pointers meet with no mismatches → palindrome.”

⚡ Full Approach (Step-by-Step, No Code)
Step 1 — Initialize Two Pointers

Set:

L = 0 (start of the string)

R = len(word) − 1 (end of the string)

Step 2 — Compare Characters

While L < R:

If word[L] == word[R] → good, keep moving toward the middle

If they differ → instantly return false

Step 3 — Move Pointers

After each comparison:

Increment L

Decrement R

This gradually checks symmetrical positions.

Step 4 — Reaching the Middle

If the loop completes without finding a mismatch →
The string is a palindrome → return true

🧠 Mental Picture

Imagine folding a string from both ends toward the center.
If all mirrored characters match perfectly → palindrome.

Example:

racecar
L-----R (r == r)
 L---R  (a == a)
  L-R   (c == c)
   center

⏱️ Complexity
Operation	Cost
Time	O(n)
Space	O(1)

Only scans the string once, using constant memory.

