word = True remembers when to stop.”

👉 Union-Find (Disjoint Set Union - DSU)

Efficiently track connected components and merge groups while keeping everything fast and balanced.

✨ Flashcard

“Each node points upward.
Root = group leader.
Flatten while climbing.
Attach small under big.”

⚡ Full Explanation (Very Easy)

1️⃣ Initialization

🎯 Goal

Start with n separate nodes — each in its own group.

🔍 How it works

• Every node begins as its own parent
• Every node starts with height (rank) = 0

So initially:

1   2   3   4
↑   ↑   ↑   ↑


Everyone is their own leader.

🧠 Mental Map

“Everyone starts alone.”

2️⃣ Finding a Leader (Find Operation)

🎯 Goal

Figure out which group a node belongs to.

🔍 How it works

• Start from the node
• Move upward through parents
• Stop when you reach a node that points to itself

That node is the root (leader).

⚡ Path Compression (The Speed Trick)

While climbing:

• Make each node skip its parent
• Point it closer to the root

This flattens the structure.

Instead of:

1 → 2 → 3 → 4


It gradually becomes:

1 → 4
2 → 4
3 → 4


Future searches become extremely fast.

🧠 Mental Map

“Climb to the leader.
Shorten the ladder while climbing.”

3️⃣ Merging Two Groups (Union Operation)

🎯 Goal

Combine two different groups into one.

🔍 How it works

• Find the leader of node A
• Find the leader of node B
• If same leader → already connected
• If different → attach one tree under the other

⚡ Union by Rank (Balance Control)

To prevent long chains:

• Attach smaller-height tree under taller tree
• If same height → attach one and increase height by 1

This keeps trees shallow.

🧠 Mental Map

“Small tree goes under big tree.”

⭐ Why Rank + Path Compression Together Are Powerful

Without them:

1 → 2 → 3 → 4 → 5


Find becomes slow.

With both optimizations:

Tree becomes flat.

Each operation becomes almost constant time.

📦 Complexity

• Each operation ≈ O(1) in practice
• More precisely: O(α(n))
(Inverse Ackermann — grows so slowly it's basically constant)

🚀 When Is Union-Find Used?

Union-Find is used when you need to:

1️⃣ Detect Cycles in Graphs

If connecting two nodes that already have the same leader → cycle detected.

Common in:
• Undirected graph cycle detection
• Kruskal’s Minimum Spanning Tree

2️⃣ Find Number of Connected Components

Example:
• Number of provinces
• Number of friend circles
• Network connectivity problems

3️⃣ Dynamic Connectivity Problems

When connections are added over time and you must quickly check:

“Are these two nodes connected?”

4️⃣ Kruskal’s Algorithm (Minimum Spanning Tree)

Before adding an edge:
• Check if it forms a cycle
• If not → union them

5️⃣ Grid Problems

Examples:
• Number of islands
• Surrounded regions
• Accounts merge
• Redundant connection

🧠 One-Line Intuition

“Union-Find remembers groups.
Find tells you the leader.
Union merges leaders efficiently.”

👉 Segment Tree - Node Based

Efficiently handle range queries + point updates in logarithmic time.

Perfect when:

You need many range sums

And values change over time

