👉 Dijkstra – Min Heap (Priority Queue)

Compute shortest distances from a source to all nodes in a weighted directed graph using a min-heap.

✨ Flashcard

“Heap decides next node to explore. Update distances → push to heap → explore neighbors.”

⚡ Full Explanation (Very Easy)

1. Build adjacency list

Goal
Store graph in a format that allows fast neighbor access.

🔍 How the code works (Line-by-Line)

adj = {i: [] for i in range(1, n+1)}
for s, d, w in edges:
    adj[s].append((d, w))

adj → dictionary: key = node, value = list of (neighbor, weight)

Loop over edges → add directed edges to adjacency list

🧠 Mental Map
“Adjacency list = who is connected to whom, and at what cost.”

📦 Complexity
Time: O(E) | Space: O(V + E)

2. Initialize distances

Goal
Track shortest known distance to each node from src.

🔍 How the code works

dist = {i: float("inf") for i in range(1, n+1)}
dist[src] = 0

All nodes → infinity (unknown distance)

Source → 0 (starting point)

🧠 Mental Map
“∞ everywhere, except start = 0.”

📦 Complexity
Time: O(V) | Space: O(V)

3. Initialize min-heap

Goal
Pick the next node with smallest distance to explore.

🔍 How the code works

minHeap = [(0, src)]

Heap stores (current_distance, node)

Always pops the node with minimum distance first

🧠 Mental Map
“Heap = next fastest runner to explore.”

📦 Complexity
Time: O(1) for push initially | O(log V) per later push

4. Process nodes

Goal
Explore nodes in distance order until all shortest paths are found.

🔍 How the code works

while minHeap:
    currDist, node = heapq.heappop(minHeap)
    if currDist > dist[node]:
        continue

Pop node with smallest currDist

If currDist > dist[node] → skip outdated entry

🧠 Mental Map
“Heap may contain old entries → ignore if distance is already better.”

📦 Complexity
Time: O(V log V + E log V) total

5. Explore neighbors

Goal
Relax edges and update shortest distances.

🔍 How the code works

for nei, weight in adj[node]:
    newDist = currDist + weight
    if newDist < dist[nei]:
        dist[nei] = newDist
        heapq.heappush(minHeap, (newDist, nei))

For each neighbor → calculate potential new distance

If shorter → update dist and push to heap

🧠 Mental Map
“Update distance → tell heap to explore this node later.”

📦 Complexity
Time: O(E log V) (heap push per edge)

6. Return distances

Goal
Provide shortest paths from source to all nodes.

return dist

🧠 Mental Map
“Distance table is ready → done!”

📦 Complexity
Time: O(1) | Space: O(V)

💡 Key Insight for Interviews

dist stores knowledge → shortest distances found so far

heap drives exploration → always pick the next most promising node

Must push neighbor after updating distance → otherwise Dijkstra won’t explore the new shortest path


